    "studyCard": {
      "title": "The Most Important Sentence in the Old Testament",
      "hook": "When Jesus was asked which commandment was greatest, he quoted Deuteronomy 6:4-5 — a passage so central to Jewish identity that devout Jews recite it twice daily, wear it on their bodies, and post it on their doorframes.",
      "teaching": "Deuteronomy 5 presents the Ten Commandments for the second time in the Pentateuch — the first being Exodus 20. The restating is not mere repetition; it is recontextualisation. Moses is speaking to the second generation, and he frames the commandments with extraordinary pastoral urgency: 'The Lord our God made a covenant with us at Horeb. It was not with our ancestors that the Lord made this covenant, but with us, with all of us who are alive here today.' The covenant is not historical. It belongs to this generation as much as to the one that stood at Sinai.\n\nThe most significant difference between the Deuteronomy and Exodus versions of the Ten Commandments is in the Sabbath commandment. In Exodus 20:11, the Sabbath is grounded in creation — God rested on the seventh day. In Deuteronomy 5:15, the Sabbath is grounded in the Exodus — 'Remember that you were slaves in Egypt and that the Lord your God brought you out of there with a mighty hand and an outstretched arm. Therefore the Lord your God has commanded you to observe the Sabbath day.' The same commandment, two different rationales. Creation logic says rest because God rested. Liberation logic says rest because you were slaves and are slaves no longer. Both are true. Deuteronomy foregrounds the liberation dimension.\n\nDeuteronomy 6 opens with what Jews call the Shema — from the Hebrew word for 'hear' that begins the passage. 'Hear, O Israel: The Lord our God, the Lord is one.' This single sentence has been at the heart of Jewish faith for three millennia. It is the first prayer a Jewish child learns and the last words a devout Jew hopes to speak before death. It is sewn into the mezuzah on every Jewish doorpost and bound in the tefillin worn during morning prayer. When Jesus was asked the greatest commandment, he quoted what immediately follows: 'Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your strength.'\n\nThe instruction in Deuteronomy 6:6-9 is one of the most practical passages in the entire book: 'These commandments that I give you today are to be on your hearts. Impress them on your children. Talk about them when you sit at home and when you walk along the road, when you lie down and when you get up. Tie them as symbols on your hands and bind them on your foreheads. Write them on the doorframes of your houses and on your gates.' The commands are not confined to the sanctuary, the synagogue, or the festival. They are woven into the ordinary rhythm of daily life — morning, evening, home, road, work, rest. The Torah is a twenty-four-hour curriculum.\n\nDeuteronomy 6:20-25 provides a scripted answer to the question 'What is the meaning of the stipulations, decrees and laws the Lord our God has commanded you?' Moses does not answer with theology or philosophy. He answers with history: 'We were slaves of Pharaoh in Egypt, but the Lord brought us out of Egypt with a mighty hand.' The meaning of the law is the story of redemption. The commandments make sense only within the narrative of what God has done. This is consistent with the Exodus 20 preamble: 'I am the Lord your God who brought you out of Egypt.' Obedience is always the response to grace, never its precondition.",
      "keyVerse": "Hear, O Israel: The Lord our God, the Lord is one. Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your strength. — Deuteronomy 6:4-5 (NIV)",
      "memoryPrompt": "The Shema is not just a creed — it is a curriculum: morning, evening, home, road, hands, forehead, doorpost, gate. The love of God is a twenty-four-hour practice.",
      "challengeFact": "Deuteronomy 5:15 grounds the Sabbath commandment in the Exodus rather than in creation — a significant difference from Exodus 20:11, making the Sabbath simultaneously a creation ordinance and a liberation declaration, with Deuteronomy emphasising the freedom dimension that Exodus does not."
    },
